        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>How to: Rotate an Object by Using a Geometric Path (Matrix Animation)</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>This example shows how to use a              <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.MatrixAnimationUsingPath&gt;</ph> and a              <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.MatrixTransform&gt;</ph> to rotate (pivot) an object along a geometric path defined by a              <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.PathGeometry&gt;</ph> object.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Example</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example uses the                      <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.MatrixAnimationUsingPath&gt;</ph> object to animate the                      <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.MatrixTransform.Matrix%2A&gt;</ph> property of a                      <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.MatrixTransform&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The                      <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.MatrixTransform&gt;</ph> is applied to a button and causes it to move along a curved path.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Because the                      <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.MatrixAnimationUsingPath.DoesRotateWithTangent%2A&gt;</ph> property is set to                      <ph id="ph2">`true`</ph>, the rectangle rotates along the tangent of the path.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>For the complete sample, see                      <bpt id="p1">[</bpt>Path Animation Sample<ept id="p1">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=160028)</ept>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The code version of the preceding sample used a                      <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Storyboard&gt;</ph> to animate the                      <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.EllipseGeometry&gt;</ph>, even though only one animation was applied.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>An easier way to apply a single animation to a property in code is to use the                      <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Animatable.BeginAnimation%2A&gt;</ph> method.</source>
        </trans-unit>
